n":[{"type":"text","value":"isn’t","position":{"start":{"line":25,"column":238,"offset":2777},"end":{"line":25,"column":243,"offset":2782},"indent":[]}}],"position":{"start":{"line":25,"column":236,"offset":2775},"end":{"line":25,"column":245,"offset":2784},"indent":[]}},{"type":"text","value":" correct. Although that distinction might sound a bit unnecessary, I assure you it is not. Typechecking is difficult because you have to consider ","position":{"start":{"line":25,"column":245,"offset":2784},"end":{"line":25,"column":391,"offset":2930},"indent":[]}},{"type":"strong","children":[{"type":"text","value":"every incorrect program possible","position":{"start":{"line":25,"column":393,"offset":2932},"end":{"line":25,"column":425,"offset":2964},"indent":[]}}],"position":{"start":{"line":25,"column":391,"offset":2930},"end":{"line":25,"column":427,"offset":2966},"indent":[]}},{"type":"text","value":", and try to eliminate each one. It’s almost impossible to get right, and there are probably dozens of logic errors in Oak’s type system ","position":{"start":{"line":25,"column":427,"offset":2966},"end":{"line":25,"column":564,"offset":3103},"indent":[]}},{"type":"emphasis","children":[{"type":"text","value":"right now","position":{"start":{"line":25,"column":565,"offset":3104},"end":{"line":25,"column":574,"offset":3113},"indent":[]}}],"position":{"start":{"line":25,"column":564,"offset":3103},"end":{"line":25,"column":575,"offset":3114},"indent":[]}},{"type":"text","value":". ","position":{"start":{"line":25,"column":575,"offset":3114},"end":{"line":25,"column":577,"offset":3116},"indent":[]}},{"type":"emphasis","children":[{"type":"text","value":"But","position":{"start":{"line":25,"column":578,"offset":3117},"end":{"line":25,"column":581,"offset":3120},"indent":[]}}],"position":{"start":{"line":25,"column":577,"offset":3116},"end":{"line":25,"column":582,"offset":3121},"indent":[]}},{"type":"text","value":", in the end, it works pretty well. It’s mostly just the fringe